{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-bdce966df0891562", "type": "tool_result", "content": "=== paper 2604.00292 ===\n# MambaVoiceCloning: Efficient and Expressive Text-to-Speech via State-Space Modeling and Diffusion Control\narXiv: 2604.00292\nAuthors: Sahil Kumar, Namrataben Patel, Honggang Wang, Youshan Zhang\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: tts_vc\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. A diffusion-based TTS system with a fully SSM-only inference-time conditioning path spanning text, rhythm, and prosody under a fixed decoder.\n  2. A gated bidirectional Mamba fusion with AdaLN that improves long-range prosody stability and reduces drift on multi-sentence and out-of-distribution text.\n  3. Protocol- and capacity-matched baselines that isolate the architectural impact of removing inference-time attention.\n  4. A deployment-oriented analysis covering memory usage, throughput, SSM hyperparameter sensitivity, long-form behavior, and finite look-ahead streaming, demonstrating predictable linear-time characteristics.\n\nTags: TTS, TTS/架构-NAR-Diffusion, TTS/控制-参考语音, TTS/功能-流式\n=== paper 2005.08100 ===\n# Conformer: Convolution-augmented Transformer for Speech Recognition\narXiv: 2005.08100\nAuthors: Anmol Gulati, James Qin, Chung-Cheng Chiu, Niki Parmar, Yu Zhang, Jiahui Yu, Wei Han, Shibo Wang, Zhengdong Zhang, Yonghui Wu, Ruoming Pang\nYear: 2020 | Venue: \nTopic: asr\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Proposes the Conformer architecture that organically combines convolution neural networks and transformers to model both local and global dependencies in an audio sequence in a parameter-efficient way.\n  2. Introduces a novel Conformer block featuring a multi-headed self-attention module and a convolution module sandwiched between two Macaron-style feed-forward modules with half-step residual connections.\n  3. Integrates relative sinusoidal positional encoding into the multi-headed self-attention module to improve generalization across varying input lengths.\n  4. Achieves state-of-the-art word error rates of 1.9%/3.9% on the LibriSpeech test-clean/test-other benchmarks using an external language model.\n  5. Demonstrates parameter efficiency by showing that a 30M-parameter Conformer model outperforms a 139M-parameter Transformer Transducer.\n  6. Provides comprehensive ablation studies validating the superiority of the Macaron-style feed-forward structure, depthwise convolutions, and stacking the convolution module after the self-attention module.\n\nTags: ASR\n=== paper 2510.12827 ===\n# Automatic Speech Recognition in the Modern Era: Architectures, Training, and Evaluation\narXiv: 2510.12827\nAuthors: Md. Nayeem, Md Shamse Tabrej, Kabbojit Jit Deb, Shaonti Goswami, Md. Azizul Hakim\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: \nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. A systematic review of the dominant end-to-end ASR architectures, including CTC, attention-based encoder-decoders, RNN-T, and Transformer/Conformer models.\n  2. A detailed analysis of modern training paradigms, tracing the evolution from supervised methods and data augmentation to self-supervised and weakly-supervised learning.\n  3. A comprehensive summary of the key datasets, benchmarks, and evaluation metrics used to measure and compare ASR system performance.\n  4. An examination of practical deployment challenges and a discussion of critical ethical considerations, including system robustness, fairness, and data privacy.\n\nTags: ASR, ASR/显式对齐-CTC, ASR/隐式对齐-AED, ASR/显式对齐-RNNT, ASR/训练-监督, ASR/训练-SSL微调, ASR/训练-弱监督\n=== paper 2303.03329 ===\n# End-to-End Speech Recognition: A Survey\narXiv: 2303.03329\nAuthors: Rohit Prabhavalkar, Takaaki Hori, Tara N. Sainath, Ralf Schlüter, Shinji Watanabe\nYear: 2023 | Venue: \nTopic: \nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Provides a comprehensive taxonomy of end-to-end ASR models categorized by how they handle alignment between acoustic frames and output labels.\n  2. Presents architectural improvements to basic end-to-end models, including model combinations, contextual biasing, advanced encoder/decoder structures, and integrated endpointing.\n  3. Details training aspects of end-to-end models, covering alignment handling, external language model integration, minimum error training, pretraining, and regularization.\n  4. Reviews decoding algorithms for end-to-end models, distinguishing between frame-synchronous and label-synchronous beam search, as well as various model fusion and vectorization techniques.\n  5. Discusses external language model types and their integration methods into end-to-end ASR, ranging from shallow and deep fusion to internal language model estimation.\n  6. Analyzes the relationship between end-to-end and classical HMM-based ASR systems, comparing their modeling properties, training paradigms, and performance trends.\n  7. Demonstrates the real-world deployment of end-to-end models in on-device production systems, highlighting latency and accuracy trade-offs.\n\nTags: ASR, ASR/显式对齐-CTC, ASR/显式对齐-RNNT\n=== paper 2502.12900 ===\n# Soundwave: Less is More for Speech-Text Alignment in LLMs\narXiv: 2502.12900\nAuthors: Yuhao Zhang, Zhiheng Liu, Fan Bu, Ruiyu Zhang, Benyou Wang, Haizhou Li\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: audio_understanding\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We propose an efficient training framework that utilizes only ten thousand hours of training data to achieve state-of-the-art speech understanding performance.\n  2. We introduce dynamic multi-task learning in the post-training stage to enhance speech modeling and leverage the benefits of text data.\n  3. We annotate a sound classification dataset to support the alignment between sound and text, and provide high-quality instruction data based on the thinking process for speech LLMs.\n\nTags: LALM, ASR, LALM/潜在表示, LALM/理解型, ASR/显式对齐-CTC\n=== paper 1912.07875 ===\n# Libri-Light: A Benchmark for ASR with Limited or No Supervision\narXiv: 1912.07875\nAuthors: Jacob Kahn, Morgane Rivière, Weiyi Zheng, Evgeny Kharitonov, Qiantong Xu, Pierre-Emmanuel Mazaré, Julien Karadayi, Vitaliy Liptchinsky, Ronan Collobert, Christian Fuegen, Tatiana Likhomanenko, Gabriel Synnaeve, Armand Joulin, Abdelrahman Mohamed, Emmanuel Dupoux\nYear: 2019 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_dataset\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We introduce Libri-Light, a large open-source corpus of over 60K hours of unlabelled English speech derived from open-source audio books.\n  2. We provide audio segmented by voice activity detection and tagged with SNR, speaker ID, and genre descriptions.\n  3. We establish a common benchmark with evaluation metrics for three settings: zero resource/unsupervised (ABX), semi-supervised (PER, CER), and distant supervision (WER).\n  4. We offer limited-resource training sets containing 10 minutes, 1 hour, and 10 hours of aligned textual resources to facilitate low-resource ASR research.\n  5. We evaluate distant supervision using the standard LibriSpeech dev and test sets to enable direct comparison with supervised state-of-the-art systems.\n  6. We provide baseline systems for the unsupervised, semi-supervised, and distant supervision settings using modified CPC and TDS models.\n\nTags: ASR, SSL, Eval, ASR/训练-SSL微调, Eval/基准\n=== paper 1912.06670 ===\n# Common Voice: A Massively-Multilingual Speech Corpus\narXiv: 1912.06670\nAuthors: Rosana Ardila, Megan Branson, Kelly Davis, Michael Henretty, Michael Kohler, Josh Meyer, Reuben Morais, Lindsay Saunders, Francis M. Tyers, Gregor Weber\nYear: 2019 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_dataset\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Presentation of Common Voice, a massively-multilingual, crowd-sourced speech corpus released under a public domain license.\n  2. Implementation of a scalable data collection and validation pipeline that organically supports new languages through community effort.\n  3. Demonstration of multilingual automatic speech recognition via transfer learning, yielding an average Character Error Rate improvement across twelve target languages.\n  4. Publication of the first ever end-to-end automatic speech recognition results for the majority of the twelve investigated target languages.\n\nTags: ASR", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "c276bda4-4e9c-4ce9-bcaf-25f10595a8f5", "uuid": "5d4c9708-afa8-4fb1-8cfb-c7faa6f0fc68", "timestamp": "2026-07-06T09:29:39.923Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "=== paper 2604.00292 ===\n# MambaVoiceCloning: Efficient and Expressive Text-to-Speech via State-Space Modeling and Diffusion Control\narXiv: 2604.00292\nAuthors: Sahil Kumar, Namrataben Patel, Honggang Wang, Youshan Zhang\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: tts_vc\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. A diffusion-based TTS system with a fully SSM-only inference-time conditioning path spanning text, rhythm, and prosody under a fixed decoder.\n  2. A gated bidirectional Mamba fusion with AdaLN that improves long-range prosody stability and reduces drift on multi-sentence and out-of-distribution text.\n  3. Protocol- and capacity-matched baselines that isolate the architectural impact of removing inference-time attention.\n  4. A deployment-oriented analysis covering memory usage, throughput, SSM hyperparameter sensitivity, long-form behavior, and finite look-ahead streaming, demonstrating predictable linear-time characteristics.\n\nTags: TTS, TTS/架构-NAR-Diffusion, TTS/控制-参考语音, TTS/功能-流式\n=== paper 2005.08100 ===\n# Conformer: Convolution-augmented Transformer for Speech Recognition\narXiv: 2005.08100\nAuthors: Anmol Gulati, James Qin, Chung-Cheng Chiu, Niki Parmar, Yu Zhang, Jiahui Yu, Wei Han, Shibo Wang, Zhengdong Zhang, Yonghui Wu, Ruoming Pang\nYear: 2020 | Venue: \nTopic: asr\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Proposes the Conformer architecture that organically combines convolution neural networks and transformers to model both local and global dependencies in an audio sequence in a parameter-efficient way.\n  2. Introduces a novel Conformer block featuring a multi-headed self-attention module and a convolution module sandwiched between two Macaron-style feed-forward modules with half-step residual connections.\n  3. Integrates relative sinusoidal positional encoding into the multi-headed self-attention module to improve generalization across varying input lengths.\n  4. Achieves state-of-the-art word error rates of 1.9%/3.9% on the LibriSpeech test-clean/test-other benchmarks using an external language model.\n  5. Demonstrates parameter efficiency by showing that a 30M-parameter Conformer model outperforms a 139M-parameter Transformer Transducer.\n  6. Provides comprehensive ablation studies validating the superiority of the Macaron-style feed-forward structure, depthwise convolutions, and stacking the convolution module after the self-attention module.\n\nTags: ASR\n=== paper 2510.12827 ===\n# Automatic Speech Recognition in the Modern Era: Architectures, Training, and Evaluation\narXiv: 2510.12827\nAuthors: Md. Nayeem, Md Shamse Tabrej, Kabbojit Jit Deb, Shaonti Goswami, Md. Azizul Hakim\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: \nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. A systematic review of the dominant end-to-end ASR architectures, including CTC, attention-based encoder-decoders, RNN-T, and Transformer/Conformer models.\n  2. A detailed analysis of modern training paradigms, tracing the evolution from supervised methods and data augmentation to self-supervised and weakly-supervised learning.\n  3. A comprehensive summary of the key datasets, benchmarks, and evaluation metrics used to measure and compare ASR system performance.\n  4. An examination of practical deployment challenges and a discussion of critical ethical considerations, including system robustness, fairness, and data privacy.\n\nTags: ASR, ASR/显式对齐-CTC, ASR/隐式对齐-AED, ASR/显式对齐-RNNT, ASR/训练-监督, ASR/训练-SSL微调, ASR/训练-弱监督\n=== paper 2303.03329 ===\n# End-to-End Speech Recognition: A Survey\narXiv: 2303.03329\nAuthors: Rohit Prabhavalkar, Takaaki Hori, Tara N. Sainath, Ralf Schlüter, Shinji Watanabe\nYear: 2023 | Venue: \nTopic: \nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Provides a comprehensive taxonomy of end-to-end ASR models categorized by how they handle alignment between acoustic frames and output labels.\n  2. Presents architectural improvements to basic end-to-end models, including model combinations, contextual biasing, advanced encoder/decoder structures, and integrated endpointing.\n  3. Details training aspects of end-to-end models, covering alignment handling, external language model integration, minimum error training, pretraining, and regularization.\n  4. Reviews decoding algorithms for end-to-end models, distinguishing between frame-synchronous and label-synchronous beam search, as well as various model fusion and vectorization techniques.\n  5. Discusses external language model types and their integration methods into end-to-end ASR, ranging from shallow and deep fusion to internal language model estimation.\n  6. Analyzes the relationship between end-to-end and classical HMM-based ASR systems, comparing their modeling properties, training paradigms, and performance trends.\n  7. Demonstrates the real-world deployment of end-to-end models in on-device production systems, highlighting latency and accuracy trade-offs.\n\nTags: ASR, ASR/显式对齐-CTC, ASR/显式对齐-RNNT\n=== paper 2502.12900 ===\n# Soundwave: Less is More for Speech-Text Alignment in LLMs\narXiv: 2502.12900\nAuthors: Yuhao Zhang, Zhiheng Liu, Fan Bu, Ruiyu Zhang, Benyou Wang, Haizhou Li\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: audio_understanding\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We propose an efficient training framework that utilizes only ten thousand hours of training data to achieve state-of-the-art speech understanding performance.\n  2. We introduce dynamic multi-task learning in the post-training stage to enhance speech modeling and leverage the benefits of text data.\n  3. We annotate a sound classification dataset to support the alignment between sound and text, and provide high-quality instruction data based on the thinking process for speech LLMs.\n\nTags: LALM, ASR, LALM/潜在表示, LALM/理解型, ASR/显式对齐-CTC\n=== paper 1912.07875 ===\n# Libri-Light: A Benchmark for ASR with Limited or No Supervision\narXiv: 1912.07875\nAuthors: Jacob Kahn, Morgane Rivière, Weiyi Zheng, Evgeny Kharitonov, Qiantong Xu, Pierre-Emmanuel Mazaré, Julien Karadayi, Vitaliy Liptchinsky, Ronan Collobert, Christian Fuegen, Tatiana Likhomanenko, Gabriel Synnaeve, Armand Joulin, Abdelrahman Mohamed, Emmanuel Dupoux\nYear: 2019 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_dataset\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We introduce Libri-Light, a large open-source corpus of over 60K hours of unlabelled English speech derived from open-source audio books.\n  2. We provide audio segmented by voice activity detection and tagged with SNR, speaker ID, and genre descriptions.\n  3. We establish a common benchmark with evaluation metrics for three settings: zero resource/unsupervised (ABX), semi-supervised (PER, CER), and distant supervision (WER).\n  4. We offer limited-resource training sets containing 10 minutes, 1 hour, and 10 hours of aligned textual resources to facilitate low-resource ASR research.\n  5. We evaluate distant supervision using the standard LibriSpeech dev and test sets to enable direct comparison with supervised state-of-the-art systems.\n  6. We provide baseline systems for the unsupervised, semi-supervised, and distant supervision settings using modified CPC and TDS models.\n\nTags: ASR, SSL, Eval, ASR/训练-SSL微调, Eval/基准\n=== paper 1912.06670 ===\n# Common Voice: A Massively-Multilingual Speech Corpus\narXiv: 1912.06670\nAuthors: Rosana Ardila, Megan Branson, Kelly Davis, Michael Henretty, Michael Kohler, Josh Meyer, Reuben Morais, Lindsay Saunders, Francis M. Tyers, Gregor Weber\nYear: 2019 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_dataset\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Presentation of Common Voice, a massively-multilingual, crowd-sourced speech corpus released under a public domain license.\n  2. Implementation of a scalable data collection and validation pipeline that organically supports new languages through community effort.\n  3. Demonstration of multilingual automatic speech recognition via transfer learning, yielding an average Character Error Rate improvement across twelve target languages.\n  4. Publication of the first ever end-to-end automatic speech recognition results for the majority of the twelve investigated target languages.\n\nTags: ASR", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
